image.altText: the former premier of new south wales gladys berejiklian stands outdoors behind microphones speaking to the media

props.synopsis: In June, the corruption watchdog found Ms Berejiklian had engaged in serious corrupt conduct. At the time her supporters criticised the decision, urging her to appeal.

title.children: Former NSW premier Gladys Berejiklian takes legal action against the ICAC

image.altText: an image of the harbour bridge from 2009 showing the traffic lanes with cars, trains and trucks crossing

props.synopsis: From October 29, drivers will pay $4.27 to use the Sydney Harbour Bridge and Tunnel, a rise of 27 cents from when it last went up in 2009.

title.children: First toll rise in 14 years for Sydney Harbour Bridge and Tunnel 'very moderate', all about 'equity'

image.altText: Rupert smiles as he walks alongside Rebekah.

props.synopsis: With a career spanning 70 years, Rupert Murdoch is no stranger to facing the same kind of interviewing and investigative treatment that he has dished out in his media outlets.

title.children: 'I'm rather sick of snobs': In 1971, Murdoch gave Four Corners a no-holds-barred interview about his empire

image.altText: People take part in a rally against the voice to parliament in Brisbane

props.synopsis: Hundreds of people attend unofficial No vote rallies across Australia ahead of the Voice to Parliament referendum on October 14.

title.children: Protesters gather in major cities, calling for No vote in Voice referendum

image.altText: Sam O'Connor holds a Yes badge in front of a bookcase.

props.synopsis: The 32-year-old Liberal MP is supporting the Indigenous Voice to Parliament in one of Australia's conservative heartlands.

title.children: Sam O'Connor doesn't feel like a radical but he knows he's facing an uphill battle

image.altText: Dead wallaby on a roadside

props.synopsis: A one-year trial for roadside posts that emit a high-pitched sound to ward off animals whenever cars approach has concluded, and the results are turning heads.

title.children: Roadkill is up 20pc in NSW, but one council believes its virtual fence offers a solution

image.altText: Blacklisted Research

props.synopsis: An obscure 1980s documentary about the Indigenous land rights movement has become a clarion call for those opposing the Voice to Parliament. An ABC Investigations analysis has traced how a debunked conspiracy theory about communists was weaponised to divide voters on the referendum.

title.children: White supremacists are using an obscure 40-year-old documentary to split the Voice vote

image.altText: Tony Abbott wears a dark suit and tie

props.synopsis: Lachlan Murdoch welcomes the nomination in one of his first public statements since succeeding his father as Fox Corp's executive officer.

title.children: Former prime minister Tony Abbott nominated for Fox Corporation board of directors

image.altText: Three AFL players in navy blue come together and celebrate

props.synopsis: Brisbane and Carlton meet for a crunch preliminary final at the Gabba, with Collingwood awaiting the winner in next week's decider. Follow live.

title.children: Blues opening burst blows open prelim against the Lions

image.altText: Two army personnel standing outside a brick home.

props.synopsis: In the audio, a North Charleston resident is heard calmly explaining that a pilot just parachuted into his backyard while the pilot says he doesn't know what became of his F-35 jet.

title.children: 'I'm not sure where the airplane is': Pilot tells 911 operator he has just parachuted into backyard

image.altText: On the left, a gold bar. On the right, Bob Menendez is dressed in a tuxedo, Nadine Menendez in a red dress.

props.synopsis: Cash, gold, a convertible and a "low- or no-show job" were allegedly used to bribe US senator Bob Menendez and his wife, in exchange for favours to benefit the Egyptian government and help a trio of businessmen.

title.children: A powerful senator, his 'consultant' wife and kilos of gold: The Egyptian bribery scandal that's hit US congress

image.altText: Sogavare speaking at UN

props.synopsis: Solomon Islands Prime Minister Manasseh Sogavare has declined a White House invitation to meet with US President Joe Biden at next week's Pacific leaders' summit.

title.children: Solomon Islands PM snubs meeting with Biden, praises China's 'global security initiative'

image.altText: A watercolour image of the placenta and umbilical cord.

props.synopsis: In the pre-modern world, there existed a variety of words and concepts used to understand the placenta. By studying this past knowledge, we can see the echoes of attitudes to this organ in our modern science and culture.

title.children: How did a 16th-century Italian anatomist come up with the word 'placenta'? It reminded him of a cake

image.altText: Emerald Lake in Canada.

props.synopsis: Plenty of young Australians are living the dream of working abroad but many struggle to find a safe place to live or a job that pays the bills, particularly in busy tourist hotspots like Banff or London.

title.children: It's known best for picture-perfect views but Canada's Rockies hide a dire housing crisis

image.altText: an orange map with faces of northern territory people popping out

props.synopsis: The Northern Territory has the highest proportion of Indigenous people out of all the states and territories. This is what they think of the Voice to Parliament referendum.

title.children: This is what Indigenous Australians in remote NT communities think of the Voice

image.altText: a man wearing swimmers sits on the side of a harbour pool in sydney while looking at this phone

props.synopsis: The ABC's national weather wrap is back, as our meteorologist Tom Saunders breaks down why the declaration of El Niño and a positive Indian Ocean Dipole doesn't guarantee a dry summer.

title.children: El Niño summers show no swing towards wet or dry for majority of Australia

image.altText: A solar system installer adjusts solar panels on the roof of a house.

props.synopsis: The rise of rooftop solar in Australia shows no signs of slowing, bringing cheap, clean power. But the technology is also reshaping the power system in some surprising ways.

title.children: Generators pay to stay on as dominant rooftop solar 'cannibalises' electricity prices

image.altText: A sun-washed image of a herd of cattle marching across bare dry ground.

props.synopsis: Australian cattle producers are already getting drought prices. What happens when El Niño bites?

title.children: El Niño is back and cattle prices are melting

image.altText: a composite image with three panels: a sports car, Troy Hunt wearing sunglasses and a waterfront house.

props.synopsis: He's just "a dude on the web", but Troy Hunt has ended up playing an oddly central role in global cybersecurity.

title.children: Why the FBI calls this Gold Coast man when it finds a trove of stolen data

image.altText: Adelaide Crows AFLw players celebrate a goal against GWS.

props.synopsis: Adelaide encounters minimal trouble as it posts a dominant 69-point win over GWS at Canberra's Manuka Oval.

title.children: Crows thrash Giants to continue hot start to AFLW season, wins for Tigers, Cats

image.altText: A young man and his dog pose in front of a light aircraft in regional WA.

props.synopsis: Hayden McDonald, 22, is hoping to break misconceptions about autism on his 14,000km journey around the country, stopping at regional communities and schools along the way.

title.children: Young pilot blazing a trail for autistic aviators touches down in outback NSW

image.altText: A man looks at the camera, with his hands raised and palms facing the camera

props.synopsis: Russell Brand has spent years standing in the space between conspiracy theories and wellness online — this is why he wants you there with him.

title.children: Russell Brand speaks for first time amid sexual assault claims — and his choice of platform is revealing

image.altText: A mother with blonde hair sits next to her dog and daughter, who is reading a book

props.synopsis: Homeless people are threatened with fines and even jail time as councils crack down on those forced to sleep in car parks amid a nationwide housing crisis.

title.children: 'Where do they want us to go?': Councils crack down on car sleepers at peak of homelessness crisis

image.altText: a female artist wearing wide rimmed glassed looks at the camera outdoors

props.synopsis: A struggle for identity and culture took the hip-hop artist and songwriter back home to Zambia where she reclaimed her story, she's back showcasing her African roots at a new Sydney festival.

title.children: Sampa The Great is back in Australia and bringing her two homes together

image.altText: A composite image of a wombat close up with cracked, sore eyes and ears, and a young man holding a big net.

props.synopsis: Toby Davidson first saw a wombat with mange when he was eight years old, near his parents' property north-west of Sydney. Its cracked, bleeding eyes spurred him on to save other animals from the same plight.

title.children: When a video of Toby saving wombats went viral, he quit his job to do it full-time

image.altText: A swarm of red fire ants.

props.synopsis: Fire ants are a real pain. Their name is based on what it feels like to be stung by one — but it is far from the biggest pain in the insect world.

title.children: What's Australia's worst insect stinger? Hint: it's not the dreaded fire ant

image.altText: A man in a dark blue polo shirt, laughing and looking over his shoulder.

props.synopsis: Eight-time grand prix winner Daniel Ricciardo joined AlphaTauri in the middle of this season, replacing Dutch rookie Nick De Vries.

title.children: Two Aussies on the F1 grid in 2024 as Ricciardo re-signs with Italian team

image.altText: Red and blue tinted image of a rover on the moon

props.synopsis: India is yet to establish contact with its Moon rover and lander as a new lunar day arrives, weeks after putting the two to "sleep".

title.children: India struggles to wake up Moon rover and lander after successful landing

image.altText: A stylised portrait of a young man with brown hair flowing down across his body.

props.synopsis: Warracknabeal-based Ben Fowler's first NFT digital artwork sold for $930 within days. Now he and other regional artists are cashing in on the opportunities of blockchain technology.

title.children: How NFTs are creating a new global marketplace for regional artists like Ben

image.altText: A woman looking at her kindle

props.synopsis: As China's economy remains in the doldrums, more and more young people see social media influencer as a legitimate career option, but experts question the industry's sustainability.

title.children: Rainbow quit her job to become a full-time social media influencer and now earns up to $20,000 a month

image.altText: A man with grey hair and a beard wearing a blue button up shirt standing in front of a vegetable gardening smiling.

props.synopsis: A South Australian man helps make a regional community centre more dementia-friendly — in a bid to fight isolation faced by many living with the condition.

title.children: Bruce felt isolated after his dementia diagnosis, now he's helping to break the stigma for others
